IBM DELIVERY MANAGEMENT — STATUS REPORTING, RAG, AND ESCALATION
================================================================
Source: IBM public delivery frameworks, project management best practices
Last updated: 2026

IBM RAG STATUS REPORTING
--------------------------
RAG stands for Red, Amber, Green. It is the standard IBM project health reporting system
used across all IBM consulting engagements. Every IBM project status report includes
RAG indicators for each key delivery dimension.

RAG STATUS DEFINITIONS (IBM STANDARD):

GREEN — On track
- Project is meeting budget targets within approved tolerance (typically ±5%)
- All milestones on schedule or ahead
- No unresolved risks or issues that threaten delivery
- Stakeholder satisfaction is positive
- Team velocity is stable
Action: Monitor and maintain. Continue weekly reporting.

AMBER — At risk, corrective action required
- One or more dimensions showing slippage but recoverable
- Schedule variance 6-15% behind plan
- Budget trending 6-15% over baseline
- One or more blockers active but being managed within the team
- Risk probability increasing but not yet impacting outcomes
Action: Identify root cause, assign owner, set resolution deadline within 3 business days.
PM must communicate the "route to green" plan in the weekly status report.

RED — Off plan, immediate escalation required
- Serious deviation from plan that cannot be self-resolved by the squad
- Schedule variance >15% behind plan OR milestone missed with no recovery path
- Budget overrun >15% of baseline OR requires additional IBM/client investment
- Critical blocker that requires external intervention (IBM leadership or client executive)
- Stakeholder relationship at risk
Action: Escalate to IBM Delivery Manager within 24 hours.
Executive intervention required. Recovery plan must be approved before work continues.

IBM SUB-RAG DIMENSIONS:
Each IBM status report rates the following dimensions separately:
- TIMELINE — Are we delivering on schedule?
- BUDGET — Are we within financial tolerance?
- SCOPE — Is the agreed scope being delivered?
- QUALITY — Are we meeting quality standards (defect rates, test coverage)?
- RISK — Are known risks under control?
- STAKEHOLDER — Is the client relationship healthy?
- RESOURCES — Do we have the people and tools we need?

OVERALL RAG RULE: The overall project RAG is the worst of any single dimension.
If timeline is GREEN but budget is RED, the overall status is RED.

IBM WEEKLY STATUS REPORT FORMAT
---------------------------------
Every IBM consulting engagement produces a weekly status report. Standard format:

HEADER:
- Project name and engagement code
- Reporting week (e.g., Week 4 of 12)
- Report date
- Prepared by (Delivery Manager name)
- Overall RAG status

SECTION 1 — EXECUTIVE SUMMARY (2-3 sentences)
State: overall health, key achievement this week, top concern.
Must be written for an executive who has 30 seconds to read it.
Never bury bad news in section 4. Lead with the most important thing.

SECTION 2 — RAG STATUS DASHBOARD
| Dimension   | Status | Trend | Comment                        |
|-------------|--------|-------|--------------------------------|
| Timeline    | GREEN  |  →    | Sprint 2 on track              |
| Budget      | AMBER  |  ↑    | 8% over due to env downtime    |
| Scope       | GREEN  |  →    | No change orders this week     |
| Quality     | GREEN  |  ↑    | 0 critical bugs in production  |
| Risk        | AMBER  |  →    | UAT sign-off still pending     |
| Stakeholder | GREEN  |  →    | Client engaged and positive    |

SECTION 3 — ACCOMPLISHMENTS THIS WEEK
Bullet list of what was actually completed.
Be specific — state the deliverable and its impact.
Bad: "Worked on API integration"
Good: "Completed IBM Cloud Object Storage API integration — unblocks staging deployment"

SECTION 4 — PLAN FOR NEXT WEEK
Bullet list with: task, owner name, target date.
Format: [Task description] | Owner: [Name] | Due: [Date]

SECTION 5 — RISKS AND ISSUES (RAID LOG EXTRACT)
Active risks and issues only (not closed ones).
Format: [ID] | [Description] | [Probability H/M/L] | [Impact H/H/L] | [RAG] | [Owner] | [Mitigation]

SECTION 6 — DECISIONS REQUIRED
Anything that needs client or IBM leadership decision to proceed.
Format: [Decision] | Needed by: [Date] | Owner: [Name] | Consequence if delayed: [Impact]

SECTION 7 — BUDGET STATUS
Planned spend to date vs actual spend to date.
Variance amount and percentage.
Forecast to completion vs original baseline.

IBM RAID LOG
-------------
RAID stands for Risks, Assumptions, Issues, Dependencies.
Every IBM engagement maintains a RAID log updated weekly.

RISK: Something that might happen and would negatively impact delivery.
- Probability (H/M/L), Impact (H/M/L), Score (H×H=Critical, H×M=High, etc.)
- Owner responsible for mitigation
- Mitigation action and timeline
- Contingency plan if risk materializes

ASSUMPTION: Something believed to be true but not confirmed.
- If an assumption is violated, it becomes a risk or issue
- Owner responsible for validating the assumption
- Validation deadline

ISSUE: Something that HAS happened and is impacting delivery now.
- Severity (Critical/High/Medium/Low)
- Date raised
- Owner responsible for resolution
- Resolution plan and target date

DEPENDENCY: Something the project needs from outside the squad.
- Internal dependency (another IBM workstream)
- External dependency (client team, third-party vendor, IBM IT)
- Required by date
- Risk if dependency is late

IBM ESCALATION PROCESS
------------------------

WHEN TO ESCALATE:
- A blocker is not resolved within 2 standups (48 hours)
- A risk materializes and becomes a critical issue
- Budget or timeline breach beyond approved tolerance
- Client relationship showing signs of distress
- Scope change requested that impacts agreed deliverables
- Key team member departure or unavailability

ESCALATION PATH:

LEVEL 1 — Squad Self-Resolution (0-48 hours)
The squad owns the problem. Technical Lead or QA Lead drives resolution.
Format: Flagged in daily standup. Owner assigned. Resolution target set.

LEVEL 2 — Delivery Manager Engagement (48 hours - 5 days)
If squad cannot resolve alone. Delivery Manager joins the conversation.
Delivery Manager may: unblock resources, re-prioritize sprint backlog,
engage client point of contact, adjust scope.
Format: Issue brief to Delivery Manager — problem statement, impact, options, recommendation.

LEVEL 3 — IBM Account Partner + Client Sponsor (within 24 hours of Level 2)
If issue requires client decision, additional budget, or scope change.
IBM Account Partner leads the conversation with the client executive/sponsor.
Deliverable: Formal issue escalation document + recovery options.
Client executive must respond within 48 hours.

LEVEL 4 — IBM Leadership + Client C-Suite (critical escalations only)
Project at serious risk of failure. Executive intervention required.
Requires: Formal escalation package — situation, root cause, financial impact,
recovery plan with 3 options, recommendation, decision needed.
IBM Practice Lead and IBM GBS leadership involved.

IBM CHANGE CONTROL PROCESS
----------------------------
Any change to scope, timeline, or budget requires a Change Order (CO).

CHANGE ORDER TRIGGER:
- Client requests new feature not in original SOW
- External dependency causes timeline slip beyond tolerance
- Budget adjustment needed
- Team composition change affecting delivery capacity

CHANGE ORDER PROCESS:
1. Change Request raised (by PM or client)
2. Impact assessment completed within 5 business days
   (scope impact, timeline impact, budget impact, risk impact)
3. Options presented to client: accept change (with CO), descope something else,
   or accept reduced quality
4. Client signs Change Order
5. Project plan updated, RAID log updated, status report updated

IBM WEEKLY STATUS MEETING AGENDA
----------------------------------
Recommended agenda for weekly client status meeting (30-45 minutes):

1. Opening — recap of last week's commitments (5 min)
2. RAG status walk-through — each dimension, trend, and key comment (10 min)
3. Accomplishments this week — team presents completed work (5 min)
4. Next week plan — commitments for the coming week (5 min)
5. Risks and issues — active RAID items needing client awareness (5 min)
6. Decisions needed — explicit asks from the client (5 min)
7. AOB / client questions (5 min)

GOLDEN RULES FOR IBM STATUS COMMUNICATION:
- Never surprise the client with bad news in a formal meeting
  — pre-brief the sponsor before the meeting if there is RED news
- Always bring a "route to green" plan when reporting AMBER or RED
- Be honest about status — a GREEN that is actually AMBER destroys trust faster than an AMBER
- Separate facts from opinion in reports
- Document all verbal agreements in email within 24 hours

IBM PROJECT HEALTH SCORING
----------------------------
IBM Delivery IQ uses a health score from 0-100. Mapping to RAG:

90-100: GREEN PLUS — Exceptional delivery, ahead of plan
70-89:  GREEN — On track, within tolerance
50-69:  AMBER — At risk, corrective action underway
30-49:  RED — Significant issues, escalation required
0-29:   CRITICAL RED — Project in serious jeopardy, executive intervention required

Health score inputs (weighted):
- Schedule adherence (25%)
- Budget adherence (20%)
- Scope delivery rate (20%)
- Quality metrics (15%)
- Risk score (10%)
- Stakeholder satisfaction (10%)

IBM STATEMENT OF WORK (SOW) BASICS
-------------------------------------
The SOW is the contractual document that governs every IBM consulting engagement.

Key SOW sections:
- Scope of Work — what IBM will deliver
- Deliverables — specific outputs with acceptance criteria
- Timeline — milestones and target dates
- Assumptions — what IBM assumes to be true
- Client responsibilities — what the client must provide
- Exclusions — what is explicitly NOT in scope
- Pricing — fixed fee, T&M, or outcome-based
- Change control process — how scope changes are handled
- Governance — reporting cadence and escalation path

IBM DELIVERY MANAGER RESPONSIBILITIES
---------------------------------------
The IBM Delivery Manager is accountable for the overall success of the engagement.

Weekly responsibilities:
- Produce and distribute weekly status report (RAG)
- Chair weekly status meeting with client
- Update RAID log
- Monitor budget burn rate
- Review sprint progress with Technical Lead

Ongoing responsibilities:
- Manage client relationship at sponsor level
- Own escalation decisions
- Approve Change Orders
- Ensure team has what they need to deliver
- Report to IBM Account Partner on engagement health

CLIENT RELATIONSHIP HEALTH INDICATORS
---------------------------------------
Signs of healthy client relationship:
- Client sponsor attends Sprint Playbacks
- Sponsor Users actively engaged (not just available when chased)
- Client provides timely decisions (within agreed SLAs)
- Positive tone in meetings — collaborative, not adversarial
- Client team learning Garage methods and taking ownership

Early warning signs of relationship risk:
- Client sponsor stops attending key meetings
- Decisions delayed beyond agreed timelines
- Client starting to question agreed scope
- Negative tone in emails or calls
- Client escalating directly to IBM leadership without prior notice to PM
- Sponsor User feedback becoming increasingly negative

IBM escalation rule: If three consecutive early warning signs appear,
the Delivery Manager must brief the IBM Account Partner within 48 hours.
